          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Louisville Ky,</placeName>
                                        <date>April 3d 1854</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName role="author">B H. Gotthelf</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>Walnut St. No 371</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>
                                                  <hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi>
                                        </placeName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Louisville, Kentucky,</placeName>
                                        <date>April 3, 1854</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Very honored <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>:</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Your worthy letter, as well as the books therein
                                        noted, have<lb/> arrived. For the books, I have paid $9.75
                                        in express charges which seem<lb/> to me unusually high. You
                                        must have patience till the middle day<lb/> of
                                                  <date>Passover</date>, when I shall take care to
                                        distribute the to your honor<lb/> subscribers. I shall also
                                        make an effort to sell <hi rend="underline">Dias</hi>.
                                        With<lb/> regard to the “Occident” namely, its lack of
                                        success in this town<lb/> no one is more sorry about it than
                                        I. During one year, so<lb/> many have given me notice about
                                        it that I could not even<lb/> note down their names. I have
                                        taken all sorts of trouble public<lb/> and privately to
                                        change this attitude; but in vain. When the time<lb/> for
                                        payment comes these people don't want to have it any
                                        more<lb/> The reason for this rests in the lack of a true
                                        inner culture<lb/> an old cancer, which it is not within my
                                        power to heal. The<lb/> “Asmonean” has also no more than
                                        five or six readers, and when<lb/> several months ago,
                                        someone came here to collect for it several of<lb/> these
                                        few gave it up. The gentlemen have no conception of
                                        what<lb/> means to support a work of this sort from the very
                                        beginning. In<lb/> spite of this, I shall take the trouble
                                        to do what I can at the com-<lb/>munal meeting which is to
                                        take place in our town during the<lb/> middle days of the
                                        holiday. Our friend <persName>Strauss</persName> assured
                                        me<lb/> of his cooperation. <persName>L.
                                                  Lowensohn</persName>, our secretary, complains
                                                  th<add>?</add><lb/> he has not received an
                                        “Occident” in months, in spite of the fact<lb/> that he has
                                        made inquiries about it every month at the post<lb/> office.
                                        It may be that there is another
                                                  <persName>Lowensohn</persName>, perhaps<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Dayton</placeName>, whose copies are returned to
                                        you. I beg of you to send<lb/> his copy to our secretary
                                        who, though a poor man, is a good <add>?</add><lb/> those he
                                        has missed until now I have given him.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I could not hear anything more since then about
                                                  <persName>Simon</persName><lb/> and
                                                  <persName>Oppenheimer</persName>, and you will do
                                        better therefore to retain the<lb/> copies.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Please send me, with your next letter, as soon as
                                        possible<lb/> a list of your subscribers here and in the
                                        vicinity so that I may<lb/> be in a position to make
                                        collections now and then. I should also<lb/> like to know my
                                        own standing with you. Also send me, as<lb/> cheaply as
                                        possible, two sets of your pentateuchs, with gilt<lb/>
                                        binding, a half dozen prayer-books in ordinary binding, and
                                        a half<lb/> dozen in gilt binding, the Ashkanzic ritual.
                                        Several of these<lb/> have been ordered from me for
                                                  <date>Passover</date>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr. Wise's</persName> history arouses
                                        little interest here. It<lb/> has about 50 subscribers and
                                        only 10 or even fewer have<lb/> taken up the work.
                                                  <persName>Dr. Kalisch</persName>, too, will fare
                                        no better, it<lb/> seems to me. I shall write to you in
                                        greater detail after<lb/>
                                        <date>Passover</date>—also a variety of things about the
                                        congregation</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">My wife sends you her greetings. Please send
                                        me<lb/> at once, through Adam's Express, the books I
                                        ordered, so<lb/> that I might receive them before
                                                  <date>Passover</date>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">Wishing you a happy holiday, I sign</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">most respectfully,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">Your devoted servant</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">
                                        <persName role="author">B. H. Gotthilf</persName>
                              </p>
                    </body>
